description.text:
This is a dummy battery for the Canon IXUS/SD series of digital cameras (Battery NB-4L). This was just a test to see if my initial design would fit into the camera, after some minor sanding on the edges it fits perfectly.
I plan on making some further modifications to add conductors for the battery terminals which will allow me to hook the camera up to a DC supply (there is a flap on the battery door for a cable to go through). Canon do actually sell a product that does exactly this but as you can imagine it costs a fortune. I had a quick look on eBay and the cheapest one was about two times the amount I paid for the camera.
This camera and many other Canons in this series support CHDK which is custom firmware that allows you to do some cool stuff like time-lapse and remote triggering. You soon run out of juice on a single battery which is why a DC supply is essential for any kind of real hacking.
This is part of a much bigger project which will follow up on Schmarty's work and involves some software mods to ReplicatorG and the Thing-O-Matic motherboard firmware.

Please let me know if you have any input on how I could go about adding conductors. I think I will need to hollow out the design to allow for connections, I was thinking something like nails for the conductors, inserted into the top and then solder wires to the end of the nails.

comments.text: The Canon supplied AC adaptor is rated 4.3 Volt 1.5 Amp but you can see your camera states DC3.7V on the bottom sticker (my SD600 camera's sticker states DC4.3V) so I'm thinking any voltage between those would work.

Now that I am sure and the looks have grown on me, given that the twist and lock needs tightening every 6 months I just made something to use 3m command strips to semi-permanently mount the things.  
It will probably work fine with other twist 'n' lock products but that is untested. Feedback welcome.  
New V3 uploaded, longer thread. I cant get the thread to print correctly as it is very fine but the metal nut part cuts it correct anyway.

Printed at 0.2 layers height, 15% infill and 3 shells.  
In case anybody cant figure it out, stick the thing on the wall using the command strip. The flat part should be roughly horizontal (and towards the bottom). Totally unscrew the twisting part of the croydex holder until the sucker falls out. Then put the bog roll holding part over the thread on the thing and and use the twisty part to cut a new thread into the plastic thread. Do not over tighten, you shouldn't need to, you want the main body of the croydex to just about contact the wall. Other croydex items may need to be held tighter to avoid rotation, for those I would suggest 2 sticky pads, there should be room. As with all command strip products the clue to strong adhesion is time. Leave the strip on the wall for a few hours before attaching the croydex, then leave a few hours before hanging your prized bog roll on it.

comments.text: It has occurred to me that given that in my case this is attached to tiles there is no reason to pay the extra for 3m command strips, you can use any sticky/mirror fixers as they can be removed clearly with a razor blade anyway. As they are waterproof that should allow this to be used in very wet areas like for the croydex shower stuff.

title: PowerPuck Hand-Cranked USB Charging Enclosure (IKEA flashlight hack)

description.text: Re-Packaging of low-cost IKEA LJUSA LED Flashlight (http://www.ikea.com/us/en/catalog/products/30190857/) for use charging USB devices/phones while on the go. Super capacitor design means it is lightweight but of course also means charging is more of a "real time" affair vs. charging intermediate battery first. Please let me know if this doesn't work well for you, its been awhile since I made this and I only completed one so there might be some clearance issues or things I worked around.

1) Buy the IKEA Flashlight (or two.. they are fun to have around) and acquire a suitable USB port (ie. they type that would be on your PC motherboard)
2) Print the Chassis bottom and Top (no supports)
3) Take apart flashlight and cut the two wires going to the circular LED board
4) Solder to Vcc and GND of USB Port (or directly to aUSB cable if you want to simplify
5) using flashlight screws, secure boards within their respective enclosures in the printed bottom part.
6) The super-capacitor board mounts upside down, the generator board with the gears facing up
7) plug in device and crank! *STD: This works fine for me, but you are on your own ;). Please validate this will not harm your device before using.

title: High Strength Paracord Block and Tackle Pulley

description.text: Just for fun I designed a block and tackle with the intention of seeing if I could make one strong enough to old my own weight with paracord. This design used 6 pulleys to divide my 170 lb body weight 6 times into roughly 30 lbs input force. It was strong enough but it was hard to balance! So I later designed the mount and center holder to keep everything centered. The design is also modular so you could use more or less pulleys on the block if you wanted. According to my clevis calculator (available here: http://engineerdog.com/resources/) at 50% infill (ABS) this design is rated to withstand the 550 lb load that the paracord is supposed to break at.

https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rHoh_X1mIxc Everything was printed at 30% infill and it worked just fine, but I wouldn't recommend any less than that. Make sure you tighten everything up really well, my cord kept slipping between the pulley and the body. All together you will need:
(6) 3.5" long 5/16-18 bolts
(6) 5/16-18 nylock nuts

A customizable sphere puzzle. Inspired by the Wikipedia logo.
You can put a letter or text on every piece of the sphere. In the customizer you can select from those fonts that are also available in the write.scad thing (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:16193) There are some pieces ready for download, but you can use the customizer to create pieces with your own text, or size etc. Also read the instructions. Update 2015-03-20: Now my sphere is finished. I've added some more pieces.

You can also use the customizer to create pieces and experiment with the parameters. I've published the OpenSCAD file so that you can do your own designs. (Especially for using other fonts.)  
When adding text, make sure that it does not overlap because this would interfere when putting the pieces together. (Use the text scale and offset parameters.)
Print some test pieces in order to see how they fit. If the pieces fit too tight or too loose adjust the gap parameters in your customized design.

Because this is a 3D puzzle, putting it together is not so simple as you might at first think. All pieces are slightly smaller on the inner side (toward the center of the sphere). As this also applies to the connectors you must also figure out the order of assembly even if you know the position.  
You also might have to increase the connector neck gap parameter for the last pieces in order to be able the complete the sphere. (Though for me this was not necessary.)

The customizer allows only certain fonts. If you want to use other fonts I recommend to create dxf files with ttf2dxf from
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:96714
Set the "font" parameter in the OpenSCAD script and set textMethod=0. Have fun!

title: Slightly modified Seahawks Coaster and Logo - Go Hawks!

description.text:
Go Hawks!!!!
========
I tried to print a coaster from "spondoro" before the NFC Championship game, but my temps were too low for the blue filament and it fell apart. Watching the game after a bit I was sure we were going to lose so I wouldn't have to make the coaster 'til next year, but the 'Hawks pulled through! So I had to figure out how to get it to print. In addition to fixing my temps, I decided to adjust some of the layer heights for "my" version (total ripoff of spondoro's). See Instructions To get my "layers" effect, I printed using Makerware at .2mm layer heights. The only layer that aligns with an even mm value is the green layer, so you can set a z-pause for that one but the rest need to be paused by hand or use other software or something. At my wife's request there's also the Logo at the same layers (so you can print it with a coaster), but without the coaster bit. Be careful to use temperatures appropriate for all of your filaments!
  • Start with white
  • Layer 11 (2.2mm) - Gray (slightly above 002mm)
  • Layer 13 (2.6mm) - Blue
  • Layer 15 (3.0mm) - Green (can set z-pause to 003mm)
  • Layer 19+ (3.8+mm)- Back to white (can set z-pause to 004mm - can just leave green)
    • (Optionally, start with green and then change to white at 1st mm for a green back. Also I forgot my green was glow-in-the-dark, which is cool-ish) Note that the first color change (to gray) is one layer above 002mm, so you can set pause to 002mm and then resume and only have to babysit one layer. I thought about even mm for the colors, but that's just too much depth. It needs two layers per color to look good (they bleed through some). Look at the preview for printing to get hints for what's going to be printed on the previous layer. Fortunately, the interesting stuff is currently printed last on those layers, so if you miss a little for the switch, that's OK. The last one isn't critical at all. Go Hawks!!! Of course the Logo belongs to the Seattle Seahawks, so if they ask me to, I'll take this down. Whatever part of the coaster is mine is under the Creative Commons Attribution-NonCommercial license. title: 2015 Fairy Tail Lanyard Decoration
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - No Derivatives

description.text:
A couple years back I found out about and joined the local maker community by a coincidental meeting at a local anime convention (Naka-Kon). Since Naka-Kon is coming up again in a couple of months, I started thinking that it would be great if makers had a way to identify each other at these events to find people with shared interest.  And lo, the 2015 Fairy Tail lanyard decoration was born.  
This fits right onto your lanyard for your badge for any convention you want to go to.  I'll be wearing mine around Naka-Kon this year, and it would be awesome to see others with this on as well.  Hopefully you all enjoy it.  Who knows, if it gets a big reception I might start doing one every year. ;)

There are two versions of this thing available.  One of the versions is designed for people with single extruder printers, and the other is designed for people with dual extrusion printers.  The main difference between the two is that the single extrusion system has tolerances designed in so that the parts more easily fit together.  The dual extrusion files have no tolerances and are positioned so that they will work with a dual extrusion printer.  If you end up finding that the single extrusion version is way too loose on the insert parts, you might try printing the insert portion for the dual extrusion and see how it fits.  
The main body of the print has a little built in support to assist with bridging the gap.  I found using a small flat head screw driver allows you to pop that support right out.  It shouldn't require any support in your slicing program.  
I'd recommend going really slow on this print to make sure the details come out nice and everything fits together.  It isn't that long of a print, slowing it way below my normal print speeds it still only took about 1h45m in total for both the main portion and the inserts.  
Once you have the main portion and the inserts printed, check the fit of the two.  If it pops right in and stays, Great!  Mine were a little too tight.  To take care of this, first trim any globs and any excess that may be on the bottom of the inserts from being smashed into the bed.  Then check your fit again.  If it is still a bit tight, GENTLY pound it into place with a hammer.  You probably want to hold onto the lettering with a pair of needle nose pliers when you do this to make sure they stay lined up.

  • Load tweet.svg in Inkscape
  • Save as G-Code
  • Plot
    • To Edit
  • Edit the user_card, text, and timestamp layers. You'll want to break up the groups.
  • Use the Hershey Text extension for nice single-stroke text: http://www.evilmadscientist.com/article.php/hershey
  • Plot.
    • To Change the Icon
  • Grab your Twitter icon as a .JPG
  • Import it into Inkscape.
  • Select it and use the Path | Trace Bitmap option.
  • Choose "Brightness Steps" under "Multiple Scans" and set it to 8.
  • Select the result, remove the fill, and set the stroke to black. Tweak to
    your satisfaction.

title: Excel spreadsheet to determine workable T-O-M feed rates

description.text:
This is a spreadsheet to get feed rates for your TOM into the ballpark for nice printing, based on a W/T and a layer height you choose. Flow rate is fixed at 255 PWM due to the extruder firmware and the spreadsheet also helps determine what your flowrate is.
This is a work in progress, I cannot be responsible for you totalling your TOM as some basic assumptions I have may be wrong, and my math might be crap. Thanks to Dave Durant who steered my thinking in a different direction, and gave me some impetus to think of an easier way to calibrate my 'bot.

This is meant for a stock TOM, which mine is apart from a fan duct and a relay for the dodgy DC motor. Green fields are values you need to come up with, orange are values the spreadsheet generates First, measure the speed at which the filament is pulled INTO the extruder. I simply measured 20mm intervals along the filament, marked and then started the extruder and timed it. After 6 intervals I averaged and divided by 20. This is your feed rate going in. Then measure your filament diameter (Mine was 2.92mm), extruded filament diameter (Mine was 0.6) and plug these values in. This will then give you a calculated extrusion rate (flow rate). Now this is where some funky stuff is going on. It seems based on my observations that ~13% of the volume is lost during extrusion. There are posts I've read on the MBI forums about it, and people seem to feel it's moisture absorbed by the ABS being cooked off, either that or some nasty volatiles. Regardless, this is why I repeated step one, and marked out intervals on the ingoing filament, then started extrusion and chopped a length off every time I reached a mark. 6 or so lengths of filament, average their length and then put that value in the appropriate field (Mine was 221.7mm coming out for 10mm of filament going in) This then gave me my actual, observed flow rate. Using actual and predicted flow rates I came up with the ratio (0.8716). This ratio needs refinement, as it's based on one observation at one speed and one temperature. So, subject to change. It's there for those that want to skip determining actual flow rate and just use predicted. *EDIT: 0.85 seems to be the current best ratio for determining input volume vs output volume, in my own testing 0.87 produced values for feedrate that were a little too high, I will be doing more testing to determine, but for now if you don't wish to directly measure the extrusion rate of plastic coming out of your toolhead, use 0.85 (on the unmodified spreadsheet, look for the orange field with 0.8716 and replace) Now, plug in your desired Layer height and W/T values, plus your (hopefully) approximate flow rate and the last box will be, in theory, the Feed rate you need to set to get a nice print. I threw away my current SF profile and started with a fresh one (TOM, HBP). The only modifications were the spreadsheet values, and Raft BASE and INTERFACE integers were set to 0. Outline was enabled, and First Object layer infill feed rate was set to 0.8 (bit too fast) and First object Perimeter feed rate was set to 0.55 (bit too slow). Temperature was 225C. From the look of the object, I need to fix my Z starting height ever so slightly, and probably reduce my feed rate a fraction. But it's real close! Please be nice if I've screwed up something good and proper here :P

This is a near exact model of the Dremel Idea Builder spool holder. I made it larger so that Hatchbox and other filaments can be used effectively, even as that last bit of filament gets used.   
(Even though some spools (Hatchbox) fit into the guides at the bottom of the printer without being locked into the spool holder, the spools tend to tweak and get jammed into the Z-platform as they get lighter. This model is designed to address that problem)  
This holder will lock and work with the original spool rod, or you can print another rod from the files that I uploaded.

Print with supports with the model in a vertical fashion.
Make sure to sand the interior cylinder so that the rod fits better, and the spool rolls more efficiently.
When removing the original spool holder, be aware that the nuts that hold the M2.5 screws will fall into the interior of the machine. I have gotten away with simply screwing the new holder back into the holes located at the bottom of the printer.
The screw holes and fitment holes on the bottom of the model are designed for extremely tight tolerances, and will probably need slight re-drilling to suit your needs.

title: Combined Remix of Dan0nator's Halo Pistol and MTriron slide with resized mags

description.text:
I absolutely love Dan0nator’s designs, but the devil is in the details. (UPDATE 7/4/2015) - Well, I finally got round to finishing this. Gunmetal and Metallic Black Acrylic. I don't have time for more polish and fit. The top of the Trigger needs to be trimmed in order to rotate smoothly. The magazine still needs to be shunk a bit. While it fit well, once painted it sticks. SOME RECOMMENDATIONS: Magazine Spring: Instead of trying to deal with a rubber band, I bought a spring kit from harbor depot, and one of the small compression springs worked perfectly, if you cut it shorter for the magazine. SLIDE ACTION: Also, for the slide, I drilled a hole in the slide (you can see where in the pic), and put a metal rod in to hold another harbor freight spring. I then cut off the top little cube on the back of the frame and drilled for a screw, and used a 35mm M5 screw. Mount the spring to the screw on the frame 1st. Attach a piece of string to the other end. Put the slide on with the string hanging out the back. Pull the slide just back enough to see the string, and pull the string to see the spring end, grab with some long nosed pliers and push the pin through the other end of the spring. Don't try to mount the spring the other way round (slide mounted first), as you will end up over stretching the spring. As I am using a FlashForge Creator Pro clone, some components wouldn’t fit on my bed, so I needed to slice them into different parts. Just finished the print, but haven’t gotten it complete, as I am going to do a full paint treatment to this, which is a couple weeks away from completion, but wanted to get the files up for those who are interested., as I see some folks are frustrated with the sanding needed on the mags. Also, just for ease of printing, I split up a couple of parts to they could be printed flat. So here’s what I did. Base design of course is Dan0nator’s Halo Pistol V2 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:68620 I also grabbed MTriron’s Slide W//Txt http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:536776 For the slide, I found to best get the text to print, I did a dual head print with PVA in the second head for support. Also, I needed to use some support for the rear site, as the front edge drooped on me. Other than that, I printed everything without support. Also, you will need some sanding to fit the front part of the slide into the back half of the laser site, so it can freely slide in and out. No, I haven’t sorted out the rubber band thingy to have the slide auto come forward. For the frame, I needed to chop it up to fit my bed. I then split the back portion of the frame into 2 pieces, so you could print without support. I printed the grip, the 2 parts of the laser site and hand guard without any changes. But the ends of the hand guards do need pretty good sanding to fit. But I made the trigger .4mm thinner, and it now fits in the slot without sanding. The biggest changes I made were to the magazines. They were simply too wide and too thick. This was a little tricky, because of the angle of the mags to the Z-Axis. I sorted out the rotations, and then made the mags .49mm less wide, and .45mm less thick, and they fit perfectly. I also chopped the bottoms off, so I could lay the big part of the mags on the bed, so they would be really smooth on my glass bed.
PLA Print, 2 shells, 20% fill Files are oriented in the manner I printed them.
